liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Facebook owner Meta has announced a series of measures "to address the spike in harmful and potentially harmful content" on social media. The default setting for Facebook users "in the region" will change to only allow Facebook friends to comment on new posts. New rules also make it easier for people to bulk delete comments, "lock their Facebook profile in one step" and stops comments from automatically displaying under posts. "Our policies are designed to keep people safe on our apps while giving everyone a voice," the social media giant said in a statement. "We apply these policies equally around the world and there is no truth to the suggestion that we are deliberately suppressing voice."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Meta announces new measures to tame spike in 'harmful' content

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: China said on Thursday that it was "deeply disappointed" by the United States' decision to veto a UN Security Council resolution calling for a "humanitarian pause" in the Israel-Hamas conflict. "China is deeply disappointed in the United States' obstruction of the Security Council's adoption of a draft resolution on the Palestinian issue," foreign ministry spokesperson Mao Ning said. Ms Ning called on the Security Council to "play its role in reaching a ceasefire and stopping the war". AFP

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: At least 13 Palestinians have been reported dead from the same family when an Israeli airstrike hit their house in Khan Younis. The fresh bombardment hit the building where the Al-Batta and Al-Majayda family were living, survivors told Reuters. People stood in dismay, while others panicked as they rushed to get stretchers to pull survivors. Children covered in dust were carried into ambulances. Reuters
